      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation across three systematically refined meshes yields GCI = 3.7% for NIH at the 7 L/min, 4000 RPM operating point — the condition producing highest shear stress. This exceeds the required Gradation 2 threshold. The fine-mesh solution is used for all reported predictions. Discretisation error is the dominant verified uncertainty source and is confirmed to be within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented with measurement uncertainty; flow rate uncertainty below ±3%, rotational speed uncertainty below ±1%.",
      "rationale": "Bench-scale experiments were conducted using calibrated Coriolis flow meters (±1.5% uncertainty) and optical tachometers (±0.3% uncertainty). Temperature was maintained at 37 ± 0.5 °C. Blood analogue fluid (glycerol-water, 36% v/v) was characterised rheologically prior to each test series. All five operating points were replicated in triplicate; coefficient of variation for NIH across replicates was below 6% at all conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD-predicted NIH within ±20% of experimental values at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD predictions of NIH agree with experimental measurements within ±18% across all five operating points. Maximum discrepancy occurs at 5 L/min, 3500 RPM (17.8% over-prediction), consistent with known SST k-omega over-prediction of shear stress in recirculation zones. The acceptance criterion of ±20% is satisfied at all conditions. Relative hemolysis index RH < 1 is confirmed for the device under evaluation relative to the predicate device."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (NIH, RH) are directly linked to the regulatory acceptance criterion and clinical hemolysis risk.",
      "rationale": "The normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH) are the quantities specified in the FDA guidance for blood-contacting device submissions. NIH captures the mechanistic relationship between fluid shear stress exposure and erythrocyte damage via the power-law hemolysis model. RH directly operationalises the predicate comparison required for 510(k) substantial equivalence. Both QoIs are therefore fully relevant to the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
